</arg></template><bold><italics>Spain in Flames</italics></bold><space/>is a 1937<space/><link><target>compilation film</target></link><space/>made by<space/><link><target>Helen van Dongen</target></link><space/>during the<space/><link><target>Spanish Civil War</target></link>.<extension extension_name='ref' name="obituary"><template><target>cite news</target><arg name="last">Mastrangelo<space/></arg><arg name="first">Bob<space/></arg><arg name="title">Helen van Dongen Obituary<space/></arg><arg name="work">The Guardian<space/></arg><arg name="date">10 November 2006<space/></arg><arg name="url">http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/2006/nov/10/guardianobituaries.obituaries</arg></template></extension><space/><link><target>Hal Erickson (author)</target><part>Hal Erickson</part></link><space/>has written that the film &quot;... is remarkable in its willingness to offer both sides of the conflict -- though its sympathies are firmly with the<space/><link><target>Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)</target><part>Loyalists</part></link>.&quot;<extension extension_name='ref' name="allmovie"><template><target>cite web</target><arg name="last">Erickson<space/></arg><arg name="first">Hal<space/></arg><arg name="title">Spain in Flames<space/></arg><arg name="publisher">allmovie.com<space/></arg><arg name="url">http://www.allmovie.com/work/spain-in-flames-235752<space/></arg></template></extension><space/>The film consists of two parts. The first, &quot;The Fight for Freedom&quot;, was based on film footage from a Spanish government documentary<space/><italics>Spain and the Fight for Freedom</italics>.<extension extension_name='ref' name="Schoots"><template><target>cite book</target><arg name="title">Living Dangerously: a Biography of Joris Ivens<space/></arg><arg name="last">Schoots<space/></arg><arg name="first">Hans<space/></arg><arg name="publisher">Amsterdam University Press<space/></arg><arg name="year">2000<space/></arg><arg name="page">116<space/></arg><arg name="isbn">978-90-5356-433-2<space/></arg><arg name="url">http://books.google.com/books?id</arg></template></extension></paragraph><paragraph>The second part, &quot;They Shalt Not Pass&quot;, was based on a short film<space/><italics>No Pasaran!</italics><space/>done by the Artkino Film Company of the Soviet Union, where van Dongen was working at the time the film was made.<extension extension_name='ref' name="obituary"></extension><extension extension_name='ref' name="allmovie"></extension><extension extension_name='ref' name="Schoots"></extension><space/><link><target>John Dos Passos</target></link><space/>narrated parts of the film,<extension extension_name='ref' name="obituary"></extension><space/>and the commentary was written by Dos Passos,<space/><link><target>Ernest Hemingway</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Archibald MacLeish</target></link>, and Prudencio de Pareda.<extension extension_name='ref' name="Schoots"></extension><extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>cite web</target><arg name="title">Hemingway:War in Spain and the Fifth Column<space/></arg><arg name="url">http://www.sc.edu/library/spcoll/amlit/hemingway/hem6.html<space/></arg><arg name="last1">Scott<space/></arg><arg name="first1">Patrick<space/></arg><arg name="last2">Bruccoli<space/></arg><arg name="first2">Mathew J.<space/></arg><arg name="publisher">University of South Carolina<space/></arg><arg name="year">2002<space/></arg></template><space/>Webpages based on the catalog for the Speiser and Easterling-Hallman Collection of Ernest Hemingway at the University of South Carolina.</extension><space/>Erickson writes that, &quot;The horrendous images of battlefield carnage, not to mention the close-ups of suffering and dying Spanish children, still pack a wallop when seen today.&quot;<extension extension_name='ref' name="allmovie"></extension></paragraph><paragraph>Later, Hemingway, Dos Passos,<space/><link><target>Lillian Hellman</target></link><space/>and others founded the company Contemporary Historians, which produced another film called<space/><italics><link><target>The Spanish Earth</target></link></italics><space/>(1937), directed by<space/><link><target>Joris Ivens</target></link><space/>and edited by van Dongen.</paragraph><heading level='2'>See also</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><italics><link><target>The Spanish Earth</target></link></italics><space/>(1937)</listitem><listitem><italics><link><target>Espaa 1936 (film)</target><part>Espaa 1936</part></link></italics><space/>(1937)</listitem></list><heading level='2'>References</heading><paragraph><template><target>reflist</target></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>Further reading</heading><paragraph><template><target>refbegin</target></template></paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><template><target>cite book</target><arg name="last">Carr</arg><arg name="first">Virginia Spencer</arg><arg name="authorlink">Virginia Spencer Carr</arg><arg name="title">Dos Passos: A Life</arg><arg name="url">http://books.google.com/books?id</arg><arg name="accessdate">8 December 2013</arg><arg name="year">2004</arg><arg name="publisher">Northwestern University Press</arg><arg name="isbn">978-0-8101-2200-0</arg></template></listitem><listitem><template><target>cite news</target><arg name="last">Howard</arg><arg name="first">Walter</arg><arg name="title">Anthracite Reds</arg><arg name="chapter">Civil Liberties Backs War Movie</arg><arg name="url">http://books.google.com/books?id</arg><arg name="newspaper">Wilkes-Barre Record</arg><arg name="date">26 March 1937</arg><arg name="page">307</arg><arg name="volume">2</arg><arg name="accessdate">8 December 2013</arg></template></listitem><listitem><template><target>cite book</target><arg name="last">Donaldson</arg><arg name="first">Scott</arg><arg name="title">Fitzgerald and Hemingway: Works and Days</arg><arg name="url">http://books.google.com/books?id</arg><arg name="accessdate">8 December 2013</arg><arg name="year">2011</arg><arg name="publisher">Columbia University Press</arg><arg name="isbn">978-0-231-14817-7</arg></template></listitem><listitem><template><target>cite book</target><arg name="last">Doherty</arg><arg name="first">Thomas</arg><arg name="authorlink">Tom Doherty</arg><arg name="title">Hollywood and Hitler, 1933–1939</arg><arg name="url">http://books.google.com/books?id</arg><arg name="accessdate">8 December 2013</arg><arg name="year">2013</arg><arg name="publisher">Columbia University Press</arg><arg name="isbn">978-0-231-53514-4</arg></template></listitem><listitem><template><target>cite book</target><arg name="last">Vernon</arg><arg name="first">Alex</arg><arg name="title">Hemingway’s Second War: Bearing Witness to the Spanish Civil War</arg><arg name="url">http://books.google.com/books?id</arg><arg name="accessdate">8 December 2013</arg><arg name="year">2011</arg><arg name="publisher">University of Iowa Press</arg><arg name="isbn">978-1-58729-981-0</arg></template></listitem></list><paragraph><template><target>refend</target></template></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>DEFAULTSORT:Spain In Flames</target></template><link><target>Category:1937 films</target></link><link><target>Category:Anti-fascist propaganda films</target></link><link><target>Category:Spanish Civil War films</target></link><link><target>Category:Compilation films</target></link><link><target>Category:Anthology films</target></link><link><target>Category:Features based on short films</target></link></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>war-documentary-film-stub</target></template></paragraph></article>